{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17643344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17643344"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:52:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:52:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17999"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17999","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17999"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73146"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10713"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17999"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58618"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24943"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27037"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73146"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pedicle of the spine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A cartilaginous structure cushioning the vertebrae","A short, thick bony structure connecting the vertebral body to the vertebral arch","A cylindrical structure forming the central part of the vertebral body","A thin, flat plate of bone forming the roof of the vertebral arch","A fibrous structure connecting adjacent vertebrae"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epedicle\u003C/strong\u003E of the spine is a short, thick bony structure that connects the vertebral body to the vertebral arch. It plays a crucial role in the stability and structure of the vertebral column, providing a pathway for nerves and blood vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethin, flat plate of bone\u003C/strong\u003E forming the roof of the vertebral arch is known as the lamina, not the pedicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecylindrical structure\u003C/strong\u003E forming the central part of the vertebral body is the vertebral body itself, not the pedicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efibrous structure\u003C/strong\u003E connecting adjacent vertebrae refers to ligaments, such as the interspinous or supraspinous ligaments, not the pedicle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecartilaginous structure\u003C/strong\u003E cushioning the vertebrae is the intervertebral disc, not the pedicle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pedicle of the spine is a short, thick bony structure that connects the vertebral body to the vertebral arch.","The pedicle plays a crucial role in the stability and structure of the vertebral column.","Understanding the anatomy of the spine is essential for diagnosing and managing spinal conditions."],"references":["Middleditch, A., \u0026 Oliver, J. (2005). Functional anatomy of the spine. Elsevier Health Sciences","Cramer, G. D., \u0026 Darby, S. A. (2013). Clinical anatomy of the spine, spinal cord, and ANS","Bogduk, N. (2016). Functional anatomy of the spine. Handbook of clinical neurology, 136, 675-688","Adigun OO, Reddy V, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Back, Spinal Cord. 2023 Jun 26. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725689","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58618"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17999"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58618","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58618"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T04:19:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T04:20:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10713"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73146"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}